a118-c834ad71cdc7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] in 2019 was a turning point in my life. It=E2=80=99s where Not =
Boring began, and I wouldn=E2=80=99t be writing this to you right now if I =
hadn=E2=80=99t seen a random tweet from David Perell and decided to give it=
 a shot.=C2=A0
At the time, I didn=E2=80=99t want to be a full-time writer. I just wanted =
to be a better writer, because I thought it would help me at my job, help m=
e find a new job, and give me an excuse to clarify my thoughts about a lot =
of things I was interested in and read about. It did all of that, but it al=
so led to all of this.
David is the writing teacher you secretly wish you had growing up. He=E2=80=
=99s insanely passionate, obsessed with quality, and has a way of making it=
 a ton of fun to improve your writing. Plus, there=E2=80=99s no better way =
to force yourself to improve your writing than being (virtually) around a g=
roup of people trying to do the same thing every week.=C2=A0
Write of Passage [ https://substack.com/redirect/65cc95ee-8a60-4bda-a118-c8=
34ad71cdc7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] is electric. I spoke on the last night of the course a couple cohorts =
ago, and it was so cool to see just how much people loved the experience th=
ey had. Whether you want to write professionally, meet smart, curious peopl=
e online, or just want to get better at shaping a narrative, there=E2=80=99=
s nothing I could recommend more highly than Write of Passage [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/65cc95ee-8a60-4bda-a118-c834ad71cdc7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 103rd Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Packy here. Dan is OOO drinking Spritzes in on the Italian coast (the creat=
ine business [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3938a69-a81e-4e27-8a4a-a24655=
045307?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 is good!) so I=E2=80=99m filling in to deliver your dose.=20
Let=E2=80=99s have ourselves a Friday, shall we? Start with a little optimi=
sm, get a couple hours of work in, then kick back and watch the world=E2=80=
=99s best athletes do their thing in Paris. It=E2=80=99s Olympics season ba=
by!=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
(1) A twice-yearly injection offers 100% protection against HIV, study sugg=
ests [ https://substack.com/redirect/97cf7237-c73b-4def-bcf4-c401bd551264?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Associated Press h/t @InterIntellectus [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbdc=
6a12-2bc0-4ff2-aca6-27eec0a588f8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Twice-yearly shots used to treat=C2=A0AIDS [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
2463eeb8-cc5d-4944-a8a4-71dcbc5b417b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=A0were 100% effective in preventing new i=
nfections in women, according to study results published Wednesday.
100%. That=E2=80=99s everyone. =E2=80=9CThere were no infections in the you=
ng women and girls that got the shots in a study of about 5,000=C2=A0in Sou=
th Africa [ https://substack.com/redirect/c0f08b0f-04b4-4a91-8e18-071b539ea=
df2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=C2=
=A0and Uganda, researchers reported.=E2=80=9D In a group that took daily pi=
lls, =E2=80=9Croughly 2% ended up catching HIV from infected sex partners.=
=E2=80=9D The shots worked so well that the study was stopped early so that=
 everyone could get them.=20
Despite the progress made in preventing HIV, 1.3 million people are still i=
nfected each year and 600,000 die from the disease each year, mostly in Afr=
ica.=20
The shots, Gilead=E2=80=99s Sunlenca, had been approved previously in the U=
S, Canada, and Europe as a treatment for HIV, but now that its preventative=
 strength has been shown, the race is on to make it available (and affordab=
le) for preventative care in the countries most impacted by HIV.=20
Imagine showing this article to someone in the 1980s. HIV is practically cu=
red. What a time to be alive.=20
(2) Big Week for (Open) AI=20
Last year, Llama 2 was only comparable to an older generation of models beh=
ind the frontier. This year, Llama 3 is competitive with the most advanced =
models and leading in some areas. Starting next year, we expect future Llam=
a models to become the most advanced in the industry.
The artificial intelligences are getting smarter.=20
On Tuesday, Meta released Llama 3.1 405B [ https://substack.com/redirect/ed=
a0c9fb-afbe-456d-bf31-6033d6d06c46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a monster 405 billion parameter model trained=
 on over 15 trillion tokens using 16,000 NVIDIA H100 GPUs. The elegantly-na=
med Llama 3.1 405B is competitive with best-in-class closed-source models f=
rom companies like OpenAI and Anthropic, coming in first in Instruction Fol=
lowing and second in Math (behind Claude 3.5 Sonnet and ahead of GPT-4o) ac=
cording to Scale=E2=80=99s SEAL Leaderboards [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/f4a2f1f9-ab67-498c-97e4-104d14bda08b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
As expected, they open sourced the whole thing. Along with the release, Zuc=
k penned a letter titled Open Source is the Path Forward [ http://Open Sour=
ce AI Is the Path Forward ], in which he makes the case that open source is=
 good for developers, for Meta, and for the world. Of note, he calls out Ap=
ple:
One of my formative experiences has been building our services constrained =
by what Apple will let us build on their platforms. Between the way they ta=
x developers, the arbitrary rules they apply, and all the product innovatio=
ns they block from shipping, it=E2=80=99s clear that Meta and many other co=
mpanies would be freed up to build much better services for people if we co=
uld build the best versions of our products and competitors were not able t=
o constrain what we could build.
And he argues that open models are both safer against unintentional harm, b=
ecause they=E2=80=99ll have more eyes on them, and intentional harm, becaus=
e China is probably stealing the closed model weights anyway. Zuck is reall=
y coming into his own.=20
On Wednesday, Mistral released Mistral Large 2 [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/28d413ba-9f80-4157-9bb4-f52e1a849fab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which it says beats Llama 3.1 405B on C=
oding and Math with just 123 billion parameters. The Scale SEAL Leaderboard=
 has yet to be updated, but in either case, we have some powerful open mode=
ls to work with.=20
Then yesterday, the closed models came roaring back.=20
Yesterday morning, Google Deepmind announced that its Alpha Proof and Alpha=
Geometry 2 models achieved silver-medal standard solving International Math=
ematical Olympiad problems [ https://substack.com/redirect/cf6b3317-0f49-47=
0c-86f6-43eb711c57ba?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I continue to think that while Google=E2=80=99s consumer-fa=
cing AI products have been hilariously poorly executed, the company keeps p=
umping out some of the coolest and most useful results in categories like b=
io and now math. The IMO =E2=80=9Cis the largest and most prestigious compe=
tition for young mathematicians, held annually since 1959,=E2=80=9D and it=
=E2=80=99s really hard. AI struggles with really simple math occasionally, =
so this seems like a big breakthrough, and one step closer to using AI to h=
elp solve the really big problems.=20
And finally, yesterday afternoon, OpenAI, not to be left out, shared Search=
GPT [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b9a91e3-4bf3-4cfe-b099-7b4db7bca712?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which =
is an AI-powered search engine that looks a lot like Perplexity [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/23f13e08-4763-4ce3-9818-6282b4d54fdc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Sam Altman also tweete=
d [ https://substack.com/redirect/12cce889-bba6-4625-a3a7-3f059149a222?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that the c=
ompany will begin rolling out alpha rollouts of its voice product next week=
=2E=20
It=E2=80=99s interesting to see the big foundation model companies carving =
out slightly different niches on models that seem to perform roughly at the=
 same level: OpenAI is focused on product (although I can=E2=80=99t wait to=
 see GPT-5), Anthropic is focused on product as well, bringing more into my=
 favorite model (Claude 3.5 Sonnet), Meta and Mistral are focused on open s=
ource, and Google Deepmind is focused on really hard math and science probl=
ems.=20
Bring on the competition. I=E2=80=99m trying to hang out with Dan in Italy =
while the AIs do my job.=20
(3) AI models collapse when trained on recursively generated data [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/cd744c0a-b8c7-48ef-87b4-35c54776ed65?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Shumailov, Shumaylov, Zhao, Papernot, Anderson, and Gal in Nature
Indeed, the value of data collected about genuine human interactions with s=
ystems will be increasingly valuable in the presence of LLM-generated conte=
nt in data crawled from the Internet.
Just kidding. There will be a use for us humans after all.=20
In the midst of all the new releases, researchers published a paper in Natu=
re showing that the more AI-generated data models are trained on, the worse=
 they perform.=20
Here=E2=80=99s the argument. Current LLMs are trained on data mostly create=
d by humans.As LLMs become more common, they'll start generating a lot of c=
ontent that ends up on the internet. Future LLMs might then be trained on d=
ata that includes a mix of human-created and AI-generated content. The rese=
archers found that when this happens repeatedly (they call it "learning wit=
h generational data"), the AI models start to lose some important informati=
on about the original, human-created data. They call this problem "model co=
llapse."
Model collapse happens in two stages:=20
Early stage: The AI forgets about rare or uncommon things in the data.
Late stage: The AI's outputs become less varied and more repetitive.
Researchers are smart and there=E2=80=99s a lot of money on the line, so I=
=E2=80=99m sure that in each of the labs there are already developments und=
erway to get around the data wall that doesn=E2=80=99t simply involve dumpi=
ng AI-generated content into training sets, but I read this as another sign=
 that we won=E2=80=99t see a =E2=80=9Cfast takeoff=E2=80=9D in which AI get=
s so smart, powerful, and humanlike so quickly that we don=E2=80=99t have t=
ime to react and are all useless pets.=20
We=E2=80=99re going to end up in a Goldilocks Zone [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/b0e96c1b-21e1-46be-a473-43458e734d70?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], with super powerful tools that do w=
hat we tell them to do (and that need to keep us alive to keep creating tha=
t sweet, fresh, handcrafted data).=20
(4) How to Invest Federal Funds Like a VC [ https://substack.com/redirect/8=
0a83896-bdf9-4382-9574-46fbbf59b86f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Santi Ruiz and Dr. Sandeep Patel in Statecraft
=E2=80=9CPound for pound, BARDA has easily been the most effective federal =
agency in our national COVID response.=E2=80=9D
Statecraft [ https://substack.com/redirect/27435d94-2cac-4276-a619-02e13dd2=
0c52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] i=
s one of the most fascinating newsletters on the internet. Every week, Sant=
i Ruiz interviews one person who=E2=80=99s worked inside the government mac=
hine to understand how they achieved a specific policy goal. He and guests =
have covered topics like How to Stop Losing 17,500 Kidneys [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/e6766a76-5fe4-4285-84a5-4c5b94ac7164?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], How to Buy Stuff Like DARPA=
 Does [ https://substack.com/redirect/36ef257d-b6d5-4597-93ca-41a908fc2aab?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], How t=
o Run a CIA Base in Afghanistan [ https://substack.com/redirect/916789b9-ea=
d3-4508-9dd7-91bee45eabab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and How [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d485e90-9751-=
41a0-b659-f933f48b39ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d485e90-9751-41a0-b659-f=
933f48b39ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]to Calm Oil Markets [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d485e90-9751-41a0=
-b659-f933f48b39ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ].
This week, Santi interviewed Dr. Sandeep Patel, the former Director of the =
Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority=E2=80=99s (BARDA) Di=
vision of Research, Innovation, and Ventures (DRIVe). BARDA=E2=80=99s missi=
on is to develop medical countermeasures through public-private partnership=
s for a variety of public health emergencies. DRIVe is its venture capital =
arm.=20
After I wrote about the government=E2=80=99s challenges and capitalism=E2=
=80=99s beauty [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f2e99ff-7c26-4c75-8076-88e1=
cc677e11?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] on Tuesday, a few people sent me this interview, and for good reason:=20
All of the problems that BARDA cares about, like emerging infectious diseas=
es, chemical attacks, and nuclear radiation exposure, are not commercially =
viable areas. Industry alone is not going to fund the development of medica=
l countermeasures for those things.=20
For example, BARDA funded the majority of COVID vaccine, therapeutic, and d=
iagnostic work.=20
The interview is an important reminder that there are talented, mission-dri=
ven people working behind the scenes throughout the government making sure =
that Americans are safe, healthy, and prosperous. There are certainly thing=
s that industry can=E2=80=99t solve alone. Things work better when both gov=
ernment and industry are operating at full capacity.=20
The people making everything run smoothly on the government side =E2=80=94 =
despite very real challenges working within a large, intentionally conserva=
tive organization =E2=80=94 rarely get the spotlight. Props to Santi for hi=
ghlighting their work.=20
Score one for the Deep State (laudatory).=20
(5) The benefits of GLP-1 drugs beyond obesity [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/6d8edd0f-01e2-4513-88b5-e79c99e58c50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Daniel Drucker for Science
The initial chapter of GLP-1 innovation focused on glucose control, and lat=
er, weight loss. Subsequent waves seem likely to improve health outcomes in=
 people with a range of chronic disorders. Dozens of new molecules are bein=
g interrogated in the clinic, with some likely to target new mechanisms and=
 achieve greater benefits in multiple disorders beyond simply more effectiv=
e glucose control and weight loss.
Is that? Bai gahhhh it=E2=80=99s GLP-1 again!=20
This is getting out of hand. Practically every other week, we=E2=80=99re ba=
ck with something else that GLP-1=E2=80=99s can do. Often, these new benefi=
ts seem to be the result of weight loss: people lose weight and they get he=
althier in a lot of ways. But this article suggests that it=E2=80=99s not j=
ust the weight loss.=20
The article highlights a lot of things we=E2=80=99ve covered. GLP-1s might =
reduce the risk of heart attacks and strokes, help protect the kidneys, and=
 improve liver health. It also cites some more recent studies with fascinat=
ing findings:=20
The SELECT cardiovascular outcome trial showed that semaglutide reduced hea=
rt attacks, strokes, and cardiovascular death in people with obesity, and i=
nterestingly, this benefit wasn't directly correlated with the amount of we=
ight loss.
Recent analysis of real-world data showed lower rates of suicidal ideation =
in people taking semaglutide compared to those on other glucose-lowering or=
 weight loss medications.
Analysis of electronic health records showed lower rates of cannabinoid use=
 disorder in people taking GLP-1 medications.
Aside from the weight loss mechanisms, the author suggests that GLP-1=E2=80=
=99s anti-inflammatory effects might be neuroprotective, fighting Alzheimer=
=E2=80=99s, Parkinson=E2=80=99s, and strokes, and aiding against substance =
abuse disorders and compulsive behaviors.=20
A lot of this is in the trial phase, so don=E2=80=99t get too excited just =
yet, but researchers are hopeful that next-generation therapies that combin=
e GLP-1 with other hormones or receptor targets will potentially achieve ev=
en greater benefits.=20
Guess our addiction to writing about GLP-1s is going to be hard to kick.=20
Bonus: French Paralympian Carries Torch Using Exoskeleton [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/fc7bfb45-4b8c-428e-b0bd-0dd3a2eab045?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The Paris Olympics kick off this afternoon with the Opening Ceremony at 1:3=
0pm EST, but the olympic optimism is already pouring in.=20
On Tuesday, this video of French Paralympian, Kevin Priette, went viral. Pr=
iette, who has been paraplegic since an accident at age 11, carried the Oly=
mpic Torch through Paris wearing the Atalante X exoskeleton made by French =
medical robotics company Wandercraft. The exoskeleton uses AI to balance it=
self, allowing those who were previously unable to walk to walk while keepi=
ng their upper body free to do things like carry the Olympic Torch through =
the streets of Paris.=20
Miraculous stuff ahead of two straight weeks of peak human performance.=20
Humans rock.=20
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all. Wrap up your work, slip into something =
more comfortable, and jump on (but do not f!) your couch for a weekend full=
 of Olympics.=20
